DCEL Implementaon
The DCEL consists of three types of records:
1. Vertex records: Each vertex record stores the coordinates of a vertex and a list of
incident edges.
2. Edge records: Each edge record stores the two verces that the edge connects, a pointer
to the edge that is next in clockwise order around the rst vertex, a pointer to the edge
that is next in clockwise order around the second vertex, and pointers to the two faces
that are adjacent to the edge.
3. Face records: Each face record stores a pointer to one of the edges that bounds the face.
The DCEL data structure is ecient for a number of operaons on planar subdivisions, including
traversing the subdivision, nding the neighbours of a vertex or face, compung the intersecon
of two subdivisions, and many others.
For the given paper, we are trying to paron the given arbitrary polygon into convex parons
using DCEL. For implementaon of the algorithm we do not need the informaon of faces. To
implement verces we have created three structs Vertex (storing x,y and leaving Halfedge),
Halfedge(storing origin vertex, twin Halfedge and next, previous Halfedge). A halfedge is
basically an edge that has been divided into 2 halfedges. To store the input verces of the
polygon, we have created a class DCEL, which has two main vectors verces of type Vertex,
halfedges of type Halfedge. Class DCEL has two primary funcons add_vertex and
add_halfedge to take input and store in DCEL.
Algorithm Explanaon
This algorithm is used to paron a given simple polygon with n verces into convex polygons.
The input to the algorithm is a set of verces of the polygon, provided in clockwise order, stored
in a cyclic list P. In our case we store the input points in the verces vector of class DCEL and we
push the index of each point in the vector P. We connue to work on index and access the data
points vis the verces vector whenever required.
The algorithm works by maintaining a set of verces in l that do not contain any notches
where notch is a point that makes the polygon non convex. At each iteraon, it selects (v_i-1,
v_i+1), where v_i is the current vertex under consideraon (In the code we have taken v_i0, v_i
and v_i1 to store the indices of these verces), and checks if any of these points are a notch by
the isAcuteangle funcon dened above in the code. Only if these angles are all less than 180
that we move the verces forward and add a new vertex upcoming in p to the list l.
The algorithm connues this process unl there are only three verces remaining in P. At this
point, the polygon is already convex, and the algorithm terminates.
In case a notch is detected in the previous step, we then dene a list lpvs which is a set of
verces in p but not in l and also consists only and only of notches.
If aer the above operaons the size of LPVS is greater than 0 the algorithm proceeds to
remove the verces in LPVS that are outside the rectangle formed by the x_min, x_max, y_min,
y_max coordinates in L_m, and then checks if any vertex now le in LPVS lies inside the polygon
generated by L_m. If there is such a vertex, the algorithm obtains a set VTR of verces of L_m in
the semi plane generated by v1 and v(where v is the rst point of LPVS inside the polygon). We
now pop those verces from L_m that lie to the same side of the semi plane as that of L_last. As
soon as we nd a vertex in L_m that is on the opposite side of the semi plane we generate a
convex polygon with the current verces of L_m and update P and iteravely connue the
algorithm.
If no vertex in LPVS lies inside the polygon generated by L_m, the algorithm sets the ag
Backward to false. The algorithm then connues to the next vertex v_i+1.
If the last vertex in L_m is not equal to the vertex v_2, the algorithm writes L_m as a convex
polygon of the paron and removes the verces of L_m from P. The algorithm then proceeds
to the next convex polygon, starng with a new L_m.
The output of the algorithm is a set of convex polygons that paron the input polygon.
